04726nam a22006375i 9780520945623DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20102010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209456237 a10.1525/97805209456232doi  a(DE-B1597)648106  a(OCoLC)733997392  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a932qOCoLC222/eng/202302161 aWatts, Edward J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRiot in Alexandria :bTradition and Group Dynamics in Late Antique Pagan and Christian Communities /cEdward J. Watts; ed. by Edward J. Watts. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b5 b/w photographs, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransformation of the Classical Heritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Anatomy of a Riot -- tPart One. Historical Discourse in Intellectual Communities -- tIntroduction -- t2. Personal Legacy and Scholastic Identity -- t3. Past, Present, and Future in Late Neoplatonic Historical Discourse -- tPart Two. The Past Within and Outside Late Antique Monasteries -- tIntroduction -- t4. History and the Shape of Monastic Communities -- t5. Anti-Chalcedonian Ascetics and their Student Associates -- tPart Three. Defining the Alexandrian Bishop -- tIntroduction -- t6. Creating the Legend of the Alexandrian Bishop -- t7. Theophilus and Cyril: The Alexandrian Bishop Triumphant -- t8. Peter Mongus Struggles with the Past -- t9. Conclusion -- tAppendix 1. Dating the Riot -- tAppendix 2. How Much Should We Trust Zacharias Scholasticus? -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis innovative study uses one well-documented moment of violence as a starting point for a wide-ranging examination of the ideas and interactions of pagan philosophers, Christian ascetics, and bishops from the fourth to the early seventh century. Edward J. Watts reconstructs a riot that erupted in Alexandria in 486 when a group of students attacked a Christian adolescent who had publicly insulted the students' teachers. Pagan students, Christians affiliated with a local monastery, and the Alexandrian ecclesiastical leaders all cast the incident in a different light, and each group tried with that interpretation to influence subsequent events. Watts, drawing on Greek, Latin, Coptic, and Syriac sources, shows how historical traditions and notions of a shared past shaped the interactions and behavior of these high-profile communities. Connecting oral and written texts to the personal relationships that gave them meaning and to the actions that gave them form, Riot in Alexandria draws new attention to the understudied social and cultural history of the later fifth-century Roman world and at the same time opens a new window on late antique intellectual life.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAlexandrian school, Christian. 0aAsceticismxHistoryyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aChristian communitieszEgyptzAlexandriaxHistory. 0aEducation, AncientzEgyptzAlexandria. 0aPaganismzEgyptzAlexandriaxHistory. 0aRiotszEgyptzAlexandriaxHistory. 4aAncient. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aWatts, Edward J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052029486840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094562340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945623423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520945623/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  U